{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848455063,"sessionID":"ses_2872f3b74ffesXM8DRfJP6xLgp","part":{"id":"prt_d78d0f6f60013hoqYtRITaGycy","messageID":"msg_d78d0e974001JZr37kcjfuftUI","sessionID":"ses_2872f3b74ffesXM8DRfJP6xLgp","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_99519aea14294f04af5dbd4b","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/router/design.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/router/design.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Design: AR-009 Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: This document describes the technical implementation for the Router module (`pkg/router`) that acts as an HTTP reverse proxy, routing incoming requests to appropriate AgentRuntime or CodeInterpreter backends based on Kubernetes CRD resources.\n6: \n7: ## Architecture\n8: \n9: ### Component Structure\n10: \n11: ```\n12: pkg/router/\n13: ├── router.go                   # Main router implementation\n14: ├── router_test.go             # Unit tests\n15: ├── handler.go                 # HTTP handler for proxy requests\n16: ├── handler_test.go            # Handler tests\n17: ├── resolver.go                # Route resolution logic\n18: ├── resolver_test.go           # Resolver tests\n19: ├── health.go                  # Health check manager\n20: ├── health_test.go             # Health check tests\n21: ├── config.go                  # Configuration structures\n22: └── types.go                   # Type definitions\n23: ```\n24: \n25: ### Integration Points\n26: \n27: - **Clientset**: Uses generated `versioned.Clientset` for `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1`\n28: - **Informers**: Watches `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter` resources via `SharedInformerFactory`\n29: - **Listers**: Provides cached read access for route resolution\n30: - **HTTP Client**: Reusable connection pool for backend requests\n31: \n32: ### High-Level Flow\n33: \n34: ```\n35: ┌─────────────┐     ┌──────────────┐     ┌─────────────┐     ┌─────────────────┐\n36: │   Client    │────▶│   Handler    │────▶│  Resolver   │────▶│  RouteEntry     │\n37: │             │     │              │     │             │     │  (from routes)  │\n38: └─────────────┘     └──────────────┘     └─────────────┘     └─────────────────┘\n39:                            │                                          │\n40:                            ▼                                          ▼\n41:                     ┌──────────────┐                          ┌─────────────────┐\n42:                     │   Router     │                          │  Backend URL    │\n43:                     │  (manages    │                          │  (proxy target) │\n44:                     │   routes)    │                          │                 │\n45:                     └──────────────┘                          └─────────────────┘\n46:                            │\n47:                            ▼\n48:                     ┌──────────────┐\n49:                     │  Informers   │\n50:                     │  (watch CRs) │\n51:                     └──────────────┘\n52: ```\n53: \n54: ## Data Structures\n55: \n56: ### Router\n57: \n58: ```go\n59: type Router struct {\n60:     config          *RouterConfig\n61:     routes          sync.Map // map[string]*RouteEntry\n62:     httpClient      *http.Client\n63:     kubeClient      *versioned.Clientset\n64:     informerFactory informers.SharedInformerFactory\n65:     runtimeInformer v1alpha1.AgentRuntimeInformer\n66:     interpreterInformer v1alpha1.CodeInterpreterInformer\n67:     stopCh          chan struct{}\n68:     wg              sync.WaitGroup\n69:     mu              sync.RWMutex\n70: }\n71: ```\n72: \n73: ### RouterConfig\n74: \n75: ```go\n76: type RouterConfig struct {\n77:     KubeConfig          *rest.Config\n78:     ListenAddr          string\n79:     ReadTimeout         time.Duration\n80:     WriteTimeout        time.Duration\n81:     IdleTimeout         time.Duration\n82:     MaxConnsPerHost     int\n83:     HealthCheckInterval time.Duration\n84:     HealthCheckTimeout  time.Duration\n85:     UnhealthyThreshold  int\n86:     Namespace           string // empty means all namespaces\n87: }\n88: ```\n89: \n90: ### RouteEntry\n91: \n92: ```go\n93: type RouteEntry struct {\n94:     Name       string\n95:     Namespace  string\n96:     Kind       string // \"AgentRuntime\" or \"CodeInterpreter\"\n97:     BackendURL string\n98:     Health     HealthStatus\n99:     UpdatedAt  time.Time\n100: }\n101: ```\n102: \n103: ### HealthStatus\n104: \n105: ```go\n106: type HealthStatus struct {\n107:     Healthy             bool\n108:     LastCheck           time.Time\n109:     Error               error\n110:     ConsecutiveFailures int\n111:     mu                  sync.Mutex\n112: }\n113: ```\n114: \n115: ### RouteKey\n116: \n117: ```go\n118: // routeKey generates unique key for route storage\n119: func routeKey(namespace, kind, name string) string {\n120:     return fmt.Sprintf(\"%s/%s/%s\", namespace, kind, name)\n121: }\n122: ```\n123: \n124: ## API Contracts\n125: \n126: ### Incoming Request Format\n127: \n128: **Path Pattern:**\n129: ```\n130: /apis/runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1/namespaces/{namespace}/{resourceType}/{name}[/{subpath}]\n131: ```\n132: \n133: **Resource Types:**\n134: - `agentruntimes` → Maps to AgentRuntime CR\n135: - `codeinterpreters` → Maps to CodeInterpreter CR\n136: \n137: **Headers (added by router):**\n138: - `X-Forwarded-For`: Client IP\n139: - `X-Real-IP`: Client IP\n140: - `X-Forwarded-Host`: Original host\n141: - `X-Forwarded-Proto`: Request scheme\n142: \n143: ### Processor Interface\n144: \n145: ```go\n146: type RouterInterface interface {\n147:     Start(ctx context.Context) error\n148:     Shutdown(ctx context.Context) error\n149:     ServeHTTP(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request)\n150: }\n151: ```\n152: \n153: ### Resolve Operation\n154: \n155: **Input**: `*http.Request`\n156: \n157: **Output**: `*RouteEntry` or error\n158: \n159: **Behavior**:\n160: 1. Parse namespace, resourceType, name from path\n161: 2. Look up route from `routes` sync.Map\n162: 3. Check backend health status\n163: 4. Return RouteEntry or error\n164: \n165: ### Proxy Operation\n166: \n167: **Input**: `http.ResponseWriter`, `*http.Request`, `*RouteEntry`\n168: \n169: **Output**: error\n170: \n171: **Behavior**:\n172: 1. Build backend URL from RouteEntry.BackendURL\n173: 2. Clone request with new context\n174: 3. Add forwarding headers\n175: 4. Execute request via `httpClient.Do()`\n176: 5. Copy response headers and body\n177: 6. Handle errors appropriately\n178: \n179: ## Error Handling\n180: \n181: ### Error Types\n182: \n183: ```go\n184: var (\n185:     ErrRouteNotFound      = errors.New(\"route not found\")\n186:     ErrNoHealthyBackends  = errors.New(\"no healthy backends available\")\n187:     ErrInvalidResourceType = errors.New(\"invalid resource type\")\n188:     ErrMalformedPath      = errors.New(\"malformed request path\")\n189: )\n190: \n191: var (\n192:     ErrBackendConnection  = errors.New(\"failed to connect to backend\")\n193:     ErrBackendTimeout     = errors.New(\"backend timeout\")\n194:     ErrBackendUnavailable = errors.New(\"backend unavailable\")\n195: )\n196: ```\n197: \n198: ### Error Response Format\n199: \n200: ```go\n201: type ErrorResponse struct {\n202:     Error       string `json:\"error\"`\n203:     Code        string `json:\"code\"`\n204:     RouteName   string `json:\"routeName,omitempty\"`\n205:     Timestamp   string `json:\"timestamp\"`\n206: }\n207: ```\n208: \n209: ### HTTP Status Codes\n210: \n211: | Scenario | Status Code |\n212: |----------|-------------|\n213: | Route not found | 404 |\n214: | Invalid resource type | 400 |\n215: | Malformed path | 400 |\n216: | Backend unavailable | 502 |\n217: | No healthy backends | 503 |\n218: | Backend timeout | 504 |\n219: \n220: ### Retry Strategy\n221: \n222: - **Connection errors**: Retry with next healthy backend (max 2 retries)\n223: - **Timeout**: Mark backend unhealthy, return 504\n224: - **Permanent errors** (4xx from backend): Return immediately\n225: \n226: ### Health Check Failure Policy\n227: \n228: ```\n229: Consecutive Failures → Action\n230: 3                   → Mark unhealthy, remove from rotation\n231: 1                   → Continue serving, log warning\n232: Recovery (1 success) → Mark healthy, restore to rotation\n233: ```\n234: \n235: ## Testing Strategy\n236: \n237: ### Unit Tests\n238: \n239: **File**: `router/router_test.go`\n240: \n241: ```go\n242: // Test cases:\n243: func TestRouter_Start(t *testing.T)\n244: func TestRouter_Shutdown(t *testing.T)\n245: func TestRouter_ServeHTTP(t *testing.T)\n246: func TestRouter_routeKey(t *testing.T)\n247: ```\n248: \n249: **File**: `router/resolver_test.go`\n250: \n251: ```go\n252: // Test cases:\n253: func TestResolver_ResolveRoute_Success(t *testing.T)\n254: func TestResolver_ResolveRoute_NotFound(t *testing.T)\n255: func TestResolver_ResolveRoute_Unhealthy(t *testing.T)\n256: func TestResolver_ParsePath(t *testing.T)\n257: ```\n258: \n259: **File**: `router/health_test.go`\n260: \n261: ```go\n262: // Test cases:\n263: func TestHealthChecker_CheckHealth_Success(t *testing.T)\n264: func TestHealthChecker_CheckHealth_Failure(t *testing.T)\n265: func TestHealthChecker_MarkUnhealthy(t *testing.T)\n266: func TestHealthChecker_MarkHealthy(t *testing.T)\n267: ```\n268: \n269: **File**: `router/handler_test.go`\n270: \n271: ```go\n272: // Test cases:\n273: func TestHandler_ProxyRequest_Success(t *testing.T)\n274: func TestHandler_ProxyRequest_BackendError(t *testing.T)\n275: func TestHandler_ProxyRequest_Timeout(t *testing.T)\n276: func TestHandler_AddForwardingHeaders(t *testing.T)\n277: ```\n278: \n279: ### Test Fixtures\n280: \n281: ```go\n282: func newTestRouteEntry(name, namespace, backendURL string) *RouteEntry {\n283:     return &RouteEntry{\n284:         Name:       name,\n285:         Namespace:  namespace,\n286:         Kind:       \"AgentRuntime\",\n287:         BackendURL: backendURL,\n288:         Health:     HealthStatus{Healthy: true},\n289:         UpdatedAt:  time.Now(),\n290:     }\n291: }\n292: \n293: func newTestRouterConfig() *RouterConfig {\n294:     return &RouterConfig{\n295:         ListenAddr:          \":8080\",\n296:         ReadTimeout:         15 * time.Second,\n297:         WriteTimeout:        30 * time.Second,\n298:         IdleTimeout:         60 * time.Second,\n299:         HealthCheckInterval: 10 * time.Second,\n300:         HealthCheckTimeout:  5 * time.Second,\n301:         UnhealthyThreshold:  3,\n302:     }\n303: }\n304: ```\n305: \n306: ### Mock Setup\n307: \n308: ```go\n309: // Fake kube client for testing\n310: func newFakeKubeClient(objects ...runtime.Object) *versioned.Clientset {\n311:     return fake.NewSimpleClientset(objects...)\n312: }\n313: \n314: // Mock backend server\n315: func newMockBackend(handler http.HandlerFunc) *httptest.Server {\n316:     return httptest.NewServer(handler)\n317: }\n318: ```\n319: \n320: ### Integration Tests\n321: \n322: **File**: `router/router_integration_test.go`\n323: \n324: ```go\n325: // Test scenarios (requires kind cluster):\n326: // 1. CRD creation triggers route addition\n327: // 2. CRD deletion triggers route removal\n328: // 3. End-to-end request routing\n329: // 4. Health check removes unhealthy backend\n330: // 5. Concurrent request handling\n331: ```\n332: \n333: ### Coverage Requirements\n334: \n335: - Route resolution: 100%\n336: - Proxy handler: 100%\n337: - Health check: 100%\n338: - Error handling paths: 100%\n339: - Overall: ≥85%\n340: \n341: ## Implementation Notes\n342: \n343: ### Route Key Format\n344: \n345: Routes stored in sync.Map with key: `{namespace}/{kind}/{name}`\n346: - Kind is lowercased: `agentruntime` or `codeinterpreter`\n347: \n348: ### Labels Monitored\n349: \n350: Informer filters resources with labels:\n351: - `agentcube.volcano.sh/expose: \"true\"` (only exposed resources are routed)\n352: \n353: ### Backend URL Discovery\n354: \n355: Backend URL extracted from CR spec:\n356: - AgentRuntime: `.spec.endpoint`\n357: - CodeInterpreter: `.spec.serviceURL`\n358: \n359: ### Connection Pooling\n360: \n361: HTTP client configured with:\n362: ```go\n363: &http.Transport{\n364:     MaxConnsPerHost:     config.MaxConnsPerHost,\n365:     MaxIdleConns:        100,\n366:     MaxIdleConnsPerHost: 10,\n367:     IdleConnTimeout:     90 * time.Second,\n368: }\n369: ```\n370: \n371: ### Graceful Shutdown\n372: \n373: 1. Stop accepting new connections\n374: 2. Close idle connections\n375: 3. Wait for in-flight requests (max 30s)\n376: 4. Stop informers\n377: 5. Close Kubernetes client\n\n(End of file - total 377 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Design: AR-009 Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n\n## Overview\n\nThis document describes the technical implementation for the Router module (`pkg/router`) that acts as an HTTP reverse proxy, routing incoming requests to appropriate AgentRuntime or CodeInterpreter backends based on Kubernetes CRD resources.\n\n## Architecture\n\n### Component Structure\n\n```\npkg/router/\n├── router.go                   # Main router implementation\n├── router_test.go             # Unit tests\n├── handler.go                 # HTTP handler for proxy requests\n├── handler_test.go            # Handler tests\n├── resolver.go                # Route resolution logic\n├── resolver_test.go           # Resolver tests\n├── health.go                  # Health check manager\n├── health_test.go             # Health check tests","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/router/design.md","time":{"start":1775848455032,"end":1775848455060}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775848455086,"sessionID":"ses_2872f3b74ffesXM8DRfJP6xLgp","part":{"id":"prt_d78d0fb96001zIKo4Rpy7el6Gq","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d78d0e974001JZr37kcjfuftUI","sessionID":"ses_2872f3b74ffesXM8DRfJP6xLgp","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":20929,"input":6,"output":102,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":5040,"read":15781}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775848456958,"sessionID":"ses_2872f3b74ffesXM8DRfJP6xLgp","part":{"id":"prt_d78d102fc0014lZ3nzbZQVe22C","messageID":"msg_d78d0fbc5001TEfvhc0VoI1gry","sessionID":"ses_2872f3b74ffesXM8DRfJP6xLgp","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848458661,"sessionID":"ses_2872f3b74ffesXM8DRfJP6xLgp","part":{"id":"prt_d78d10549001T5Oo97frlu6bks","messageID":"msg_d78d0fbc5001TEfvhc0VoI1gry","sessionID":"ses_2872f3b74ffesXM8DRfJP6xLgp","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_1fa16b1d7adf448b99bfeccf","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Specification: AR-009 — Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n2: \n3: **Module:** `pkg/router`  \n4: **Language:** Go  \n5: **Size:** M  \n6: **Type:** New Feature\n7: \n8: ---\n9: \n10: ## Overview\n11: \n12: This specification defines the HTTP reverse proxy functionality for the AgentCube router module. The router will proxy HTTP requests from external clients to internal agent runtime services using Kubernetes client-go for service discovery.\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## Requirements\n17: \n18: ### R-1: Router Initialization\n19: \n20: **Given** a valid Kubernetes cluster configuration  \n21: **When** the router is initialized with a `rest.Config`  \n22: **Then** the router SHALL:\n23: - Create a clientset using `clientset.NewForConfig(config)`\n24: - Initialize the shared informer factory\n25: - Register event handlers for AgentRuntime resources\n26: - Return an error if the clientset creation fails\n27: \n28: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n29: \n30: ```gherkin\n31: Scenario: Successful router initialization with valid config\n32:   Given a valid Kubernetes rest.Config pointing to a running cluster\n33:   When NewRouter(config) is called\n34:   Then the router SHALL be initialized successfully\n35:   And the clientset SHALL be created\n36:   And the informer factory SHALL be started\n37:   And no error SHALL be returned\n38: \n39: Scenario: Router initialization fails with invalid config\n40:   Given an invalid rest.Config (e.g., unreachable API server)\n41:   When NewRouter(config) is called\n42:   Then the router SHALL fail to initialize\n43:   And an appropriate error SHALL be returned\n44:   And no resources SHALL be allocated\n45: \n46: Scenario: Router initialization with custom HTTP client\n47:   Given a rest.Config and a custom *http.Client with TLS settings\n48:   When NewRouterWithClient(config, httpClient) is called\n49:   Then the router SHALL use the provided HTTP client\n50:   And the clientset SHALL be created with the custom client\n51: ```\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ### R-2: HTTP Request Routing\n56: \n57: **Given** a running router with registered AgentRuntime services  \n58: **When** an HTTP request is received at the proxy endpoint  \n59: **Then** the router SHALL:\n60: - Extract the target service identifier from the request path/headers\n61: - Look up the corresponding AgentRuntime resource using the typed client\n62: - Forward the request to the target service's endpoint\n63: - Preserve the original request method, headers, and body\n64: - Return the proxied response to the client\n65: \n66: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n67: \n68: ```gherkin\n69: Scenario: Route request to existing AgentRuntime service\n70:   Given an AgentRuntime \"agent-a\" exists in namespace \"default\"\n71:   And the agent service is running at 10.0.0.1:8080\n72:   When an HTTP GET request is received at \"/default/agent-a/api/status\"\n73:   Then the router SHALL look up \"agent-a\" using AgentRuntimeInterface.Get()\n74:   And the request SHALL be forwarded to http://10.0.0.1:8080/api/status\n75:   And the response status code SHALL be proxied back to the client\n76:   And response headers SHALL be preserved\n77: \n78: Scenario: Route request with custom headers\n79:   Given an AgentRuntime service is running\n80:   When an HTTP request with custom headers (Authorization, Content-Type) is received\n81:   Then the router SHALL forward all headers to the target service\n82:   And the Authorization header SHALL be preserved\n83:   And the Content-Type header SHALL be preserved\n84: \n85: Scenario: Route POST request with body\n86:   Given an AgentRuntime service is running\n87:   When an HTTP POST request with JSON body is received\n88:   Then the router SHALL forward the request body unchanged\n89:   And the Content-Length header SHALL be updated appropriately\n90:   And the response SHALL be returned to the client\n91: \n92: Scenario: Route request to non-existent service\n93:   Given no AgentRuntime named \"non-existent\" exists\n94:   When a request is received for \"/default/non-existent/api\"\n95:   Then the router SHALL return HTTP 404 Not Found\n96:   And an error message SHALL indicate the service was not found\n97: \n98: Scenario: Route request to inactive service\n99:   Given an AgentRuntime exists but has no ready endpoints\n100:   When a request is received for that service\n101:   Then the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n102:   And the response SHALL indicate no healthy endpoints\n103: ```\n104: \n105: ---\n106: \n107: ### R-3: Service Discovery via Informers\n108: \n109: **Given** the router is running in a Kubernetes cluster  \n110: **When** AgentRuntime resources are created, updated, or deleted  \n111: **Then** the router SHALL:\n112: - Use the SharedInformerFactory to watch for changes\n113: - Update its internal service registry on Add events\n114: - Update endpoint information on Update events\n115: - Remove services from the registry on Delete events\n116: - Handle informer cache sync on startup\n117: \n118: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n119: \n120: ```gherkin\n121: Scenario: New AgentRuntime is added\n122:   Given the router is running with informer watches active\n123:   When a new AgentRuntime \"agent-b\" is created in namespace \"default\"\n124:   Then the informer OnAdd handler SHALL be triggered\n125:   And the service SHALL be added to the router's registry\n126:   And subsequent requests SHALL be routable to \"agent-b\"\n127: \n128: Scenario: AgentRuntime is updated\n129:   Given an AgentRuntime \"agent-a\" is registered in the router\n130:   When the AgentRuntime's endpoint IP changes from 10.0.0.1 to 10.0.0.2\n131:   Then the informer OnUpdate handler SHALL be triggered\n132:   And the router's registry SHALL be updated with the new endpoint\n133:   And subsequent requests SHALL be forwarded to 10.0.0.2\n134: \n135: Scenario: AgentRuntime is deleted\n136:   Given an AgentRuntime \"agent-a\" is registered in the router\n137:   When the AgentRuntime is deleted from the cluster\n138:   Then the informer OnDelete handler SHALL be triggered\n139:   And the service SHALL be removed from the router's registry\n140:   And subsequent requests SHALL return 404\n141: \n142: Scenario: Router startup with cache sync\n143:   Given multiple AgentRuntime resources exist in the cluster\n144:   When the router starts and initializes informers\n145:   Then WaitForCacheSync SHALL be called\n146:   And all existing AgentRuntimes SHALL be loaded into the registry\n147:   And the router SHALL be ready to serve requests after sync\n148: ```\n149: \n150: ---\n151: \n152: ### R-4: Namespace-Based Routing\n153: \n154: **Given** the router supports multi-tenancy via Kubernetes namespaces  \n155: **When** a request includes a namespace in the path  \n156: **Then** the router SHALL:\n157: - Extract the namespace from the request path (e.g., `/{namespace}/{service}/...`)\n158: - Use namespace-scoped informer listers for service lookup\n159: - Only route to services within the specified namespace\n160: - Return 404 if namespace does not exist or has no matching service\n161: \n162: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n163: \n164: ```gherkin\n165: Scenario: Route to service in specified namespace\n166:   Given AgentRuntime \"svc-a\" exists in namespace \"ns-1\"\n167:   And AgentRuntime \"svc-a\" also exists in namespace \"ns-2\" with different endpoint\n168:   When a request is received at \"/ns-1/svc-a/api\"\n169:   Then the router SHALL use AgentRuntimeLister.AgentRuntimes(\"ns-1\")\n170:   And the request SHALL be forwarded to the \"ns-1\" endpoint only\n171: \n172: Scenario: Request to non-existent namespace\n173:   Given namespace \"non-existent\" does not exist\n174:   When a request is received at \"/non-existent/svc-a/api\"\n175:   Then the router SHALL return HTTP 404 Not Found\n176:   And the error SHALL indicate namespace not found\n177: \n178: Scenario: List services in namespace\n179:   Given multiple AgentRuntimes exist in namespace \"default\"\n180:   When a request is received at \"/default/__list__\"\n181:   Then the router SHALL return a list of all services in \"default\"\n182:   And the response SHALL include service names and statuses\n183: ```\n184: \n185: ---\n186: \n187: ### R-5: Health Check Endpoint\n188: \n189: **Given** the router is running  \n190: **When** a health check request is received  \n191: **Then** the router SHALL:\n192: - Expose a `/healthz` endpoint\n193: - Return HTTP 200 if the router is healthy\n194: - Check informer cache sync status\n195: - Verify clientset connectivity\n196: - Return detailed status in response body\n197: \n198: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n199: \n200: ```gherkin\n201: Scenario: Health check when router is healthy\n202:   Given the router is running with all informers synced\n203:   When an HTTP GET request is received at \"/healthz\"\n204:   Then the router SHALL return HTTP 200 OK\n205:   And the response body SHALL indicate \"healthy\"\n206:   And the informer sync status SHALL be included\n207: \n208: Scenario: Health check when informers not synced\n209:   Given the router is starting but informers have not synced\n210:   When an HTTP GET request is received at \"/healthz\"\n211:   Then the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n212:   And the response SHALL indicate cache not synced\n213: \n214: Scenario: Health check when clientset disconnected\n215:   Given the router lost connection to Kubernetes API server\n216:   When an HTTP GET request is received at \"/healthz\"\n217:   Then the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n218:   And the response SHALL indicate API server connection issue\n219: ```\n220: \n221: ---\n222: \n223: ### R-6: Connection Pooling and Timeouts\n224: \n225: **Given** the router proxies HTTP requests to backend services  \n226: **When** establishing connections to target services  \n227: **Then** the router SHALL:\n228: - Use a configurable connection pool\n229: - Set request timeout (default: 30s)\n230: - Set idle connection timeout (default: 90s)\n231: - Reuse connections for repeated requests to same backend\n232: - Handle connection errors gracefully\n233: \n234: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n235: \n236: ```gherkin\n237: Scenario: Request completes within timeout\n238:   Given a backend service responds within 5 seconds\n239:   And the request timeout is set to 30 seconds\n240:   When a request is proxied to the backend\n241:   Then the request SHALL complete successfully\n242:   And the response SHALL be returned to the client\n243: \n244: Scenario: Request times out\n245:   Given a backend service takes 60 seconds to respond\n246:   And the request timeout is set to 30 seconds\n247:   When a request is proxied to the backend\n248:   Then the router SHALL return HTTP 504 Gateway Timeout\n249:   And the connection SHALL be closed\n250: \n251: Scenario: Connection pool exhaustion\n252:   Given the connection pool is at capacity\n253:   When a new request arrives\n254:   Then the router SHALL wait for an available connection\n255:   And if none available within timeout, return HTTP 503\n256: ```\n257: \n258: ---\n259: \n260: ### R-7: Error Handling and Logging\n261: \n262: **Given** the router handles proxied requests  \n263: **When** errors occur during routing  \n264: **Then** the router SHALL:\n265: - Log all routing decisions and errors with structured logging\n266: - Include request ID, namespace, service name, and method in logs\n267: - Return appropriate HTTP status codes for different error types\n268: - Not expose internal error details to clients\n269: \n270: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n271: \n272: ```gherkin\n273: Scenario: Log successful routing\n274:   Given a request is successfully routed to a backend\n275:   When the request completes\n276:   Then a log entry SHALL be written with level INFO\n277:   And the log SHALL include method, path, namespace, service, status code, and duration\n278: \n279: Scenario: Log routing failure\n280:   Given a request fails to route (service not found)\n281:   When the routing fails\n282:   Then a log entry SHALL be written with level ERROR\n283:   And the log SHALL include error reason and request details\n284:   And the client SHALL receive a generic error message\n285: \n286: Scenario: Log backend error\n287:   Given a backend returns HTTP 500\n288:   When the response is proxied back\n289:   Then a log entry SHALL be written with level WARN\n290:   And the log SHALL include backend status code\n291:   And the response SHALL be returned to the client unchanged\n292: ```\n293: \n294: ---\n295: \n296: ### R-8: Graceful Shutdown\n297: \n298: **Given** the router is running and handling requests  \n299: **When** a shutdown signal is received  \n300: **Then** the router SHALL:\n301: - Stop accepting new requests\n302: - Wait for in-flight requests to complete (max 30s)\n303: - Shutdown the informer factory\n304: - Close all pooled connections\n305: - Release all resources\n306: \n307: **Acceptance Scenarios:**\n308: \n309: ```gherkin\n310: Scenario: Graceful shutdown with no active requests\n311:   Given the router is running with no active requests\n312:   When a SIGTERM signal is received\n313:   Then the router SHALL stop the HTTP server\n314:   And the informer factory SHALL be shut down\n315:   And all resources SHALL be released\n316:   And the process SHALL exit with code 0\n317: \n318: Scenario: Graceful shutdown with active requests\n319:   Given the router is handling 5 in-flight requests\n320:   When a SIGTERM signal is received\n321:   Then the router SHALL wait for requests to complete (up to 30s)\n322:   And new requests SHALL be rejected with HTTP 503\n323:   And after all requests complete, shutdown SHALL proceed\n324:   And the process SHALL exit with code 0\n325: \n326: Scenario: Forceful shutdown timeout\n327:   Given the router has long-running requests (>30s)\n328:   When a SIGTERM signal is received\n329:   Then the router SHALL wait up to 30s for requests to complete\n330:   And after 30s, the router SHALL force shutdown\n331:   And the process SHALL exit with code 0\n332: ```\n333: \n334: ---\n335: \n336: ## Dependencies\n337: \n338: | Dependency | Source | Usage |\n339: |------------|--------|-------|\n340: | `k8s.io/client-go` | `client-go/` | Kubernetes API client |\n341: | `k8s.io/apimachinery` | Generated types | Resource types and metav1 |\n342: | `net/http/httputil` | Go stdlib | Reverse proxy implementation |\n343: | `go.uber.org/zap` | External | Structured logging |\n344: \n345: ---\n346: \n347: ## Testing Strategy\n348: \n349: 1. **Unit Tests**: Mock clientset and informers for router logic\n350: 2. **Integration Tests**: Use fake clientset (`clientset/versioned/fake`) with test server\n351: 3. **E2E Tests**: Deploy to test cluster with real AgentRuntime resources\n352: \n353: ---\n354: \n355: ## Security Considerations\n356: \n357: - RBAC: Router service account requires `get`, `list`, `watch` permissions on AgentRuntimes\n358: - Authentication: External authentication layer required (not in scope)\n359: - Authorization: Namespace isolation enforced by routing logic\n360: - Rate limiting: To be implemented in future iteration\n361: \n362: ---\n363: \n364: ## Open Questions\n365: \n366: 1. Should the router support WebSocket connections? (Deferred to AR-010)\n367: 2. Should request/response transformation be supported? (Out of scope)\n368: 3. Should circuit breaker pattern be implemented? (Deferred to AR-011)\n\n(End of file - total 368 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Specification: AR-009 — Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n\n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n**Type:** New Feature\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nThis specification defines the HTTP reverse proxy functionality for the AgentCube router module. The router will proxy HTTP requests from external clients to internal agent runtime services using Kubernetes client-go for service discovery.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### R-1: Router Initialization\n\n**Given** a valid Kubernetes cluster configuration  ","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775848458648,"end":1775848458658}}}}
